{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}} {{Infobox mountain | name = A' Mhaighdean | photo = A-Mhaighdean-from-Slioch.jpg | photo_caption = View of A' Mhaighdean from Slioch | elevation_m = 967 | elevation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/munros/a-mhaighdean |title= walkhighlands A' Mhaighdean |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2014 |publisher=walkhighlands.co.uk |accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> | listing = [[Munro]], [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]] | translation =the maiden | language = [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]] | prominence_m = 442 | pronunciation = {{IPA-gd|ə ˈvɤitʲan|lang}} | location = [[Highland (council area)|Highland]], [[Scotland]] | range = [[Northwest Highlands]] | topo = | easiest_route = | grid_ref_UK = NH007749 | coordinates = {{coord|57.7196|N|5.346|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | map = Scotland Highland }}
'''A' Mhaighdean''' is one of the least accessible of the [[munro]]s in northern [[Scotland]]. It is {{convert|8|mi|km}} north of [[Kinlochewe]] but most easily accessible from [[Poolewe]], taking a private road South East (pedestrian & bicycle access only) to Kernsary. A good track then leads to the causeway between the [[Fionn Loch]] and [[Dubh Loch, Gairloch|Dubh Loch]]. Follow the path eastwards to about the {{convert|1000|ft|m}} level and cross the Allt Bruthach an Esain to gain the North West ridge of the mountain.
The mountain is composed of [[gneiss]], the summit presenting the highest elevation of the [[Lewisian complex|Lewisian]]. Part of the North West ridge is capped by [[Torridonian]] [[sandstone]].
